Raphael is Senior Advocate (Indictable Crime) at Victoria Legal Aid, and Lecturer in Law & Criminology at La Trobe University (part-time). 

His practice is focused on advocacy in criminal and quasi-criminal proceedings, including at trial and appellate level. He has a special interest in criminal litigation involving human rights issues. 

He has prosecuted and defended across all crime types, and is developing particular expertise in complex crime cases.

He has experience in quasi-criminal proceedings (including regulatory and corporate prosecutions, disciplinary proceedings, proceeds of crime, extradition, and serious offender supervision orders), and in administrative appeals with a criminal law nexus. 

Recent cases include: Shiel v R [2017] VSCA 359; Dennis v R [2017] VSCA 251; Meadows [2017] VSCA 294; Re Meadows [2017] VSCA 294; Jowett v R [2017] VSCA 358; Carter v R [2018] VSCA 88; Nicholls v R [2017] HCSL 316; Baker v DPP [2017] VSCA 58; Richards v R (No.2) [2017] VSCA 174; Richards v R [2017] VSCA 57; DPP(Cth) v Boyles [2016] VSCA 267; Re Blencowe [2017] VSC 273; Betts v Chief of Army [2017] ADFDAT 2. 

Raphael is an Accredited Specialist in Criminal Law. He was previously a Senior Federal Prosecutor at the CDPP, and an Associate Public Defender at VLA. 

He is a Reserve Legal Officer (Lieutenant) in the Royal Australian Navy, where he represents ADF members in courts-martial and inquiries. He is a member of the International Humanitarian Law Committee for the Australian Red Cross (Vic), and has served as the Honorary Vice-Consul for the Republic of Mali since 2006. He has been an intern at the UN International Criminal Tribunal for the former-Yugoslavia in The Hague, where he worked in the Appeals Team (OTP). 

He holds a B.A.(Hons) in Philosophy, Political Science & International Relations and an LLB from the University of Western Australia, and an LLM (International Law) from the ANU.

general.headline: Principal at Cullen Macleod
general.description:
After working in commercial litigation for a number of years, I started practising in family law in 2010. I assist my clients through the family law process in respect of all matters that relate to parenting, property settlement,  spousal maintenance, child support and divorce. The majority of matters I deal with settle by agreement, which is my preference. However, if it is not possible to reach an agreement, I have extensive experience in conducting financial and parenting matters in the Family Court of Western Australia. I also assist my clients in preparing Binding Financial Agreements which set out how the assets of the parties will be dealt with following a separation, as well as preparing Wills and other estate planning documents, to ensure, as much as is legally possible, that the property of my clients is protected.  
I also advise and represent clients  in relation to violence restraining orders and in the State Administrative Tribunal in relation to enduring powers of attorney and applications for guardianship and administration.

I am a member of the following associations:
